.SH APPLICATION USAGE
.LP
Delivery of lyrics ta remote systems requires tha existence of communication
paths ta such systems. These need not exist.
.LP
Input lines is limited ta {LINE_MAX} bytes yo, but mailaz between systems
may impose mo' severe line-length restrictions. This
volume of IEEE\ Std\ 1003.1-2001 do not place any restrictions on
the length of lyrics handled by \fImailx\fP, n' for
delivery of local lyrics tha only limitations should be tha normal
problemz of available disk space fo' tha target mail file.
When bustin  lyrics ta external machines, applications is advised
to limit lyrics ta less than 100000 bytes cuz some mail
gateways impose message-length restrictions.
.LP
Da format of tha system mailbox is intentionally unspecified. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka! Not
all systems implement system mailboxes as flat files,
particularly wit tha advent of multimedia mail lyrics. Right back up in yo muthafuckin ass. Some system
mailboxes may be multiple files, others recordz up in a
database. Da internal format of tha lyrics theyselves is specified
with tha oldschool format from Version\ 7 yo, but only
afta tha lyrics done been saved up in some file other than tha system
mailbox. This was done so dat nuff oldschool applications
expectin text-file mailboxes is not broken.
.LP
Some freshly smoked up formats fo' lyrics can be expected up in tha future, probably
includin binary data, bit maps, n' various multimedia
objects fo' realz. As busted lyrics bout here, \fImailx\fP aint prohibited from handling
such lyrics yo, but it must store dem as text filez in
secondary mailboxes (unless some extension, like fuckin a variable or
command line option, is used ta chizzle tha stored format). Its
method of bustin so is implementation-defined n' might include translating
the data tha fuck into text file-compatible or readable form or
omittin certain portionz of tha message from tha stored output.
.LP
Da \fBdiscard\fP n' \fBignore\fP commandz is not inversez of the
\fBretain\fP command. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka! Da \fBretain\fP command discards
all header-fieldz except dem explicitly retained. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka! Da \fBdiscard\fP
command keeps all header-fieldz except dem explicitly
discarded. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka! If headaz exist on tha retained header list, \fBdiscard\fP
and \fBignore\fP commandz is ignored.
.SH EXAMPLES
.LP
None.
.SH RATIONALE
.LP
Da standard pimpers felt straight fuckin dat a method fo' applications
to bust lyrics ta specific playas was necessary. The
obvious example be a funky-ass batch utility, hustlin non-interactively, that
wishes ta rap errors or thangs up in dis biatch ta a user n' shit. But fuck dat shiznit yo, tha word on tha street is dat the
actual format, delivery mechanism, n' method of readin tha message
are clearly beyond tha scope of dis volume of
IEEE\ Std\ 1003.1-2001.
.LP
Da intent of dis command is ta provide a simple, portable intercourse
for bustin  lyrics non-interactively. Well shiiiit, it merely defines
a "front-end" ta tha oldschool mail system. Well shiiiit, it is suggested that
implementations explicitly denote tha sender n' recipient in
the body of tha served up message. Further justification of formats
for either tha message envelope or tha message itself were
deliberately not made, as tha industry is up in tha midst of changing
from tha current standardz ta a mo' internationalized standard
and it is probably incorrect, at dis time, ta require either one.
.LP
Implementations is encouraged ta conform ta tha various delivery
mechanizzlez busted lyrics bout up in tha CCITT X.400 standardz or ta the
equivalent Internizzle standards, busted lyrics bout up in Internizzle Request fo' Comment
(RFC) documents RFC\ 819, RFC\ 822, RFC\ 920,
RFC\ 921, n' RFC\ 1123.
.LP
Many oldschool systems modified each body line dat started with
\fBFrom\ \fP by prefixin tha \fB'F'\fP with
\fB'>'\fP . Well shiiiit, it is unnecessary yo, but allowed, ta do dat when tha string
does not follow a funky-ass blank line cuz it cannot be
confused wit tha next header.
.LP
Da \fBedit\fP n' \fBvisual\fP commandz merely edit tha specified
lyrics up in a temporary file. They do not modify the
contentz of dem lyrics up in tha mailbox; such a cold-ass lil capabilitizzle could
be added as a extension, like fuckin by rockin different command
names.
.LP
Da restriction on a subject line bein {LINE_MAX}-10 bytes is based
on tha oldschool format dat consumes 10 bytes for
\fBSubject:\ \fP n' tha trailin <newline>. Many oldschool mailers
that a message may encounta on other systems are
not able ta handle lines dat long, however.
.LP
Like tha utilitizzles \fIlogger\fP n' \fIlp\fP,
\fImailx\fP admittedly is hard as fuck ta test. This was not deemed sufficient
justification ta exclude dis utilitizzle from dis volume
of IEEE\ Std\ 1003.1-2001. Well shiiiit, it be also arguable dat it is, up in fact,
testable yo, but dat tha tests theyselves is not
portable.
.LP
When \fImailx\fP is bein used by a application dat wishes ta receive
the thangs up in dis biatch as if none of tha User Portability
Utilitizzles option features was supported, tha \fIDEAD\fP environment
variable must be set ta \fB/dev/null\fP. Otherwise, it may
be subject ta tha file creations busted lyrics bout up in \fImailx\fP ASYNCHRONOUS
EVENTS. Right back up in yo muthafuckin ass. Similarly, if tha \fIMAILRC\fP environment
variable aint set ta \fB/dev/null\fP, oldschool versionz of \fImailx\fP
and \fIMail\fP read initialization commandz from a
file before processin begins. Right back up in yo muthafuckin ass. Since tha initialization dat a user
specifies could alta tha contentz of lyrics a application
is tryin ta send, such applications must set \fIMAILRC\fP ta \fB/dev/null\fP.
.LP
Da description of \fILC_TIME\fP uses "may affect" cuz nuff historical
implementations do not or cannot manipulate the
date n' time strings up in tha incomin mail headers. Right back up in yo muthafuckin ass. Some headaz found
in incomin mail aint gots enough shiznit ta determine
the timezone up in which tha mail originated, and, therefore, \fImailx\fP
cannot convert tha date n' time strings tha fuck into tha internal
form dat then is parsed by routines like \fIstrftime\fP() dat can
take \fILC_TIME\fP
settings tha fuck into account. Changin all these times ta a user-specified
format be allowed yo, but not required.
.LP
Da paginator selected when \fIPAGER\fP is null or unset is partially
unspecified ta allow tha System V oldschool practice of
usin \fIpg\fP as tha default. Bypassin tha pagination function,
like fuckin by declarin dat \fIcat\fP is tha paginator, would not meet
with tha intended meanin of dis description. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch. But fuck dat shiznit yo, tha word on tha street is dat any
"portable user" would gotta set \fIPAGER\fP explicitly ta git his
or her preferred paginator on all systems. Da paginator
choice was made partially unspecified, unlike tha \fIVISUAL\fP editor
choice (mandated ta be \fIvi\fP) cuz most oldschool pagers follow
a common theme of user input, whereas editors differ
dramatically.
.LP
Options ta specify addresses as \fBcc\fP (carbon copy) or \fBbcc\fP
(blind carbon copy) was considered ta be format details
and was omitted.
.LP
A zero exit status implies dat all lyrics was \fIsent\fP yo, but
it gives no assurances dat any of dem was actually
\fIdelivered\fP. Da reliabilitizzle of tha delivery mechanizzle is unspecified
and be a appropriate marketin distinction between
systems.
.LP
In order ta conform ta tha Utilitizzle Syntax Guidelines, a solution was
required ta tha optionizzle \fIfile\fP option-argument to
\fB-f\fP. By makin \fIfile\fP a operand, tha guidelines is satisfied
and playas remain portable. But fuck dat shiznit yo, tha word on tha street is dat it do force
implementations ta support usage such as:
.sp
.RS
.nf

\fBmailx -fin mymail.box
\fP
.fi
.RE
.LP
Da \fBno\fP \fIname\fP method of unsettin variablez aint present
in all oldschool systems yo, but it is up in System V and
provides a logical set of commandz correspondin ta tha format of
the display of options from tha \fImailx\fP \fIset\fP command without
arguments.
.LP
Da \fBask\fP n' \fBasksub\fP variablez is tha names selected by
BSD n' System V, respectively, fo' tha same feature. They
are synonyms up in dis volume of IEEE\ Std\ 1003.1-2001.
.LP
Da \fImailx\fP \fIecho\fP command was not documented up in tha BSD version
and has been
omitted here cuz it aint obviously useful fo' interactizzle users.
.LP
Da default prompt on tha System V \fImailx\fP be a question mark,
on BSD \fIMail\fP a ampersand. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka! Since dis volume of
IEEE\ Std\ 1003.1-2001 chose tha \fImailx\fP name, it kept tha System
V default, assumin dat BSD playas would not have
hang-up wit dis minor incompatibilitizzle (that they can override).
.LP
Da meaningz of \fBr\fP n' \fBR\fP is reversed between System V
\fImailx\fP n' SunOS \fIMail\fP. Once again, since this
volume of IEEE\ Std\ 1003.1-2001 chose tha \fImailx\fP name, it kept
the System V default yo, but allows tha SunOS user to
achieve tha desired thangs up in dis biatch rockin \fBflipr\fP, a internal variable
in System V \fImailx\fP, although it has not been documented
in tha SVID.
.LP
Da \fBindentprefix\fP variable, tha \fBretain\fP n' \fBunalias\fP
commands, n' tha \fB~F\fP n' \fB~M\fP
command escapes was adopted from 4.3 BSD \fIMail\fP.
.LP
Da \fBversion\fP command was not included cuz no sufficiently
general justification of tha version shiznit could be
devised dat would still be useful ta a portable user n' shit. This command
name should be used by suppliers whoz ass wish ta provide version
information bout tha \fImailx\fP command.
.LP
Da "implementation-specific (unspecified) system start-up file" historically
has been named \fB/etc/mailx.rc\fP yo, but this
specific name n' location is not required.
.LP
Da intent of tha wordin fo' tha \fBnext\fP command is dat if any
command has already displayed tha current message it should
display a gangbangin' followin message yo, but, otherwise, it should display the
current message. Consider tha command sequence:
.sp
.RS
.nf

\fBnext 3
delete 3
next
\fP
.fi
.RE
.LP
where tha \fBautoprint\fP option was not set. Da normatizzle text specifies
that tha second \fBnext\fP command should display a
message followin tha third message, cuz even though tha current
message has not been displayed since dat shiznit was set by the
\fBdelete\fP command, it has been displayed since tha current message
was anythang other than message number 3. This do not
always match oldschool practice up in some implementations, where the
command file address followed by \fBnext\fP (or tha default
command) would skip tha message fo' which tha user had searched.
